<exercise checkit-seed="0002" checkit-slug="L3" checkit-title="Equivalent Statements">
    <statement>
        <p>
        Are the following statements logically equivalent? Use truth tables with the symbols P and Q to determine the answer. Make sure your tables are in the standard order.
            <ol>
                <li>(I slept well last night or I am in a bad mood) implies (I slept well last night and I am in a bad mood)</li>
                <li>(I slept well last night implies I am in a bad mood) and (I am in a bad mood implies I slept well last night)</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p> In symbols, the first statement is <m>(P \vee Q) \rightarrow (P \wedge Q)</m> and the second is <m>(P \rightarrow Q) \wedge (Q \rightarrow P)</m>. The two statements are equivalent, as you can see by the final column of their truth tables.</p>
        <m>
        \begin{array}{llcc} P &amp; Q &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; (P \vee Q) \rightarrow (P \wedge Q) \\ \hline \text{True} &amp; \text{True} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{True} &amp; \text{False} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{False} \\ \text{False} &amp; \text{True} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{False} \\ \text{False} &amp; \text{False} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \end{array}
        </m>
        <m>
        \begin{array}{llcc} P &amp; Q &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; (P \rightarrow Q) \wedge (Q \rightarrow P) \\ \hline \text{True} &amp; \text{True} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{True} &amp; \text{False} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{False} \\ \text{False} &amp; \text{True} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{False} \\ \text{False} &amp; \text{False} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \end{array}
        </m>
    </answer>
</exercise>
